      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at my mortgage statement from wells fargo and i'm kinda confused. i have a 30 year fixed at 6.5% and i want to know how much of my monthly payment is actually going to interest vs principal if i'm in year 5 compared to year 25? can u break down how that works?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mortgage payments, especially with a fixed rate, are a bit of a tricky thing, but I can certainly help you see the difference between principal and interest. In the early years, a much larger portion of your payment goes towards interest, and as you move toward the end of the loan, that shifts. Think of it like a slow-moving pile of debt, and in the beginning, most of the effort is just keeping the interest from eating up your whole payment.\n\nSo, for your 30-year fixed at 6.5%, the total monthly payment is fixed, but the split changes. In year five, you'll be paying a significant chunk toward interest, while by year twenty-five, the principal portion will be much more noticeable.\n\nTo give you the exact breakdown, you'd need the original loan amount, but I can give you the general concept. The interest calculation is based on the remaining balance, and since the balance is decreasing every month, the interest you pay each month also decreases over time.",
